    <div class="educational-section">
      <h2>Understanding the Law of Cosines</h2>
      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>The Formula</h3>
          <p>The Law of Cosines relates all three sides of a triangle with the cosine of one of its angles. The primary forms are:</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6;">
            <li><strong>c² = a² + b² - 2ab · cos(C)</strong></li>
            <li><strong>a² = b² + c² - 2bc · cos(A)</strong></li>
            <li><strong>b² = a² + c² - 2ac · cos(B)</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>When to Use It</h3>
          <p>You should use the Law of Cosines in two specific scenarios when solving triangles:</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6;">
            <li><strong>SSS (Side-Side-Side):</strong> When you know the lengths of all three sides, use the rearranged formula to find an angle.</li>
            <li><strong>SAS (Side-Angle-Side):</strong> When you know two sides and the angle between them, use it to find the third side.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Law of Cosines vs. Law of Sines</h3>
          <p>If you have a known side and its opposite known angle (e.g., Side <i>a</i> and Angle <i>A</i>), you should use the <strong>Law of Sines</strong> because it is mathematically simpler. Use the <strong>Law of Cosines</strong> only when you don't have that "matching pair" of knowns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>The Origin and Proof</h3>
          <p>The Law of Cosines is inherently linked to the Pythagorean Theorem (c² = a² + b²), which only applies to right-angled triangles. By dropping a perpendicular from one vertex of an oblique triangle to the opposite side, we create two right triangles. Using basic trigonometric ratios (sine and cosine) on these right triangles and substituting them back into the Pythagorean theorem, the 2ab · cos(C) correction factor naturally emerges. This factor perfectly accounts for how the third side stretches or shrinks when the angle deviates from 90 degrees. If angle C is exactly 90 degrees, cos(90) = 0, and the term vanishes, leaving us with the standard Pythagorean formula.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>


    <div class="educational-section">
      <h2>Advanced Concepts and Proofs</h2>
      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>The Algebraic Proof</h3>
          <p>Consider a triangle placed on a Cartesian coordinate system with vertex A at the origin (0,0) and vertex B on the positive x-axis at (c,0). Vertex C is then located at (b*cos(A), b*sin(A)). Applying the distance formula (derived from the Pythagorean theorem) to find the length of side a (the distance between B and C):</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; font-family: monospace;">
            <li>a² = (c - b*cos(A))² + (0 - b*sin(A))²</li>
            <li>a² = c² - 2bc*cos(A) + b²*cos²(A) + b²*sin²(A)</li>
            <li>a² = c² - 2bc*cos(A) + b²*(cos²(A) + sin²(A))</li>
            <li>a² = c² - 2bc*cos(A) + b²*(1)</li>
            <li>a² = b² + c² - 2bc*cos(A)</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This elegant proof demonstrates how the basic properties of geometry and algebra perfectly align to yield the Law of Cosines, a formula that stands as a fundamental pillar of trigonometry.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Historical Context</h3>
          <p>While modern algebraic notation wasn't developed until much later, the underlying geometric principles of the Law of Cosines were known to ancient mathematicians. Euclid's <em>Elements</em> (Book II, Propositions 12 and 13) contains purely geometric equivalents of the law for both obtuse and acute triangles.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">During the Middle Ages, Persian and Arab mathematicians like Al-Battani and Al-Kashi significantly advanced spherical trigonometry (where a distinct but related spherical Law of Cosines applies) for astronomical and navigational purposes. In France, the law is sometimes referred to as the <em>Théorème d'Al-Kashi</em> in recognition of his extensive work calculating accurate trigonometric tables in the 15th century.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>The Vector Dot Product Connection</h3>
          <p>In linear algebra and vector calculus, the Law of Cosines is directly analogous to the formula for the dot product (scalar product) of two vectors. If sides <strong>a</strong> and <strong>b</strong> of a triangle are represented as vectors radiating from a common point, the third side <strong>c</strong> is the vector difference (<strong>a - b</strong>).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Squaring the magnitude of vector <strong>c</strong> yields:</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; font-family: monospace;">
            <li>|c|² = (a - b) · (a - b)</li>
            <li>|c|² = |a|² + |b|² - 2(a · b)</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Since the dot product <strong>a · b</strong> equals |a||b|cos(θ), substituting this reveals the standard Law of Cosines. This connection unifies planar geometry with higher-level multidimensional vector spaces.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Avoiding the Ambiguous Case</h3>
          <p>Unlike the Law of Sines, the Law of Cosines never suffers from the "ambiguous case" (SSA) when finding an angle. Why? Because the range of the principal arccosine function (cos⁻¹) is [0, π] radians or [0°, 180°].</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This perfectly matches the possible domain of interior angles in a Euclidean triangle. Therefore, a unique cosine value maps exactly to a unique angle. A positive cosine guarantees an acute angle (< 90°), a negative cosine guarantees an obtuse angle (> 90°), and a cosine of exactly zero guarantees a right angle (90°).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This robustness is why many math instructors advise using the Law of Cosines to find the largest angle first when solving SSS triangles. It mathematically eliminates any possibility of accidentally assigning an acute angle value when the true geometry requires an obtuse angle.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Applications in Navigation and Surveying</h3>
          <p>The practical applications of the Law of Cosines are vast, extending far beyond the classroom. In marine and aviation navigation, the concept of "dead reckoning" relies heavily on these principles. If a ship travels 50 nautical miles on a heading of 045°, then turns to a heading of 120° and travels 75 nautical miles, how far is it from the starting point?</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">By drawing a triangle, calculating the included angle from the headings (which would be 105°), and applying the SAS Law of Cosines, the exact linear displacement can be found instantly.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Similarly, land surveyors use a technique called triangulation. If they need to measure the distance across an impassable obstacle like a deep river canyon, they can establish a baseline on one side, measure the angles to a prominent point on the far side using a theodolite, and use trigonometric laws (both Sines and Cosines) to compute the inaccessible distance with high precision.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Solving 3D Spatial Problems</h3>
          <p>While typically taught in 2D geometry, the Law of Cosines scales up to solve three-dimensional problems. When dealing with tetrahedrons or more complex polyhedra, you frequently need to find the angles between internal diagonal lines or adjacent faces (dihedral angles).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">By calculating the lengths of the line segments forming a triangle within the 3D space using the 3D distance formula (√(Δx² + Δy² + Δz²)), you can reduce a complex 3D angle problem into a simple 2D SSS triangle problem solvable via the Law of Cosines.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This principle is the foundation for computer graphics engines. When rendering a 3D scene, lighting calculations depend heavily on determining the angle between a light source vector and the normal vector of a polygon face. While often optimized using dot products, the underlying mathematics is pure Law of Cosines.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>


    <div class="educational-section">
      <h2>Advanced Concepts and Proofs</h2>
      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>The Algebraic Proof</h3>
          <p>Consider a triangle placed on a Cartesian coordinate system with vertex A at the origin (0,0) and vertex B on the positive x-axis at (c,0). Vertex C is then located at (b*cos(A), b*sin(A)). Applying the distance formula (derived from the Pythagorean theorem) to find the length of side a (the distance between B and C):</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; font-family: monospace;">
            <li>a² = (c - b*cos(A))² + (0 - b*sin(A))²</li>
            <li>a² = c² - 2bc*cos(A) + b²*cos²(A) + b²*sin²(A)</li>
            <li>a² = c² - 2bc*cos(A) + b²*(cos²(A) + sin²(A))</li>
            <li>a² = c² - 2bc*cos(A) + b²*(1)</li>
            <li>a² = b² + c² - 2bc*cos(A)</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This elegant proof demonstrates how the basic properties of geometry and algebra perfectly align to yield the Law of Cosines, a formula that stands as a fundamental pillar of trigonometry.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Historical Context</h3>
          <p>While modern algebraic notation wasn't developed until much later, the underlying geometric principles of the Law of Cosines were known to ancient mathematicians. Euclid's <em>Elements</em> (Book II, Propositions 12 and 13) contains purely geometric equivalents of the law for both obtuse and acute triangles.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">During the Middle Ages, Persian and Arab mathematicians like Al-Battani and Al-Kashi significantly advanced spherical trigonometry (where a distinct but related spherical Law of Cosines applies) for astronomical and navigational purposes. In France, the law is sometimes referred to as the <em>Théorème d'Al-Kashi</em> in recognition of his extensive work calculating accurate trigonometric tables in the 15th century.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>The Vector Dot Product Connection</h3>
          <p>In linear algebra and vector calculus, the Law of Cosines is directly analogous to the formula for the dot product (scalar product) of two vectors. If sides <strong>a</strong> and <strong>b</strong> of a triangle are represented as vectors radiating from a common point, the third side <strong>c</strong> is the vector difference (<strong>a - b</strong>).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Squaring the magnitude of vector <strong>c</strong> yields:</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; font-family: monospace;">
            <li>|c|² = (a - b) · (a - b)</li>
            <li>|c|² = |a|² + |b|² - 2(a · b)</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Since the dot product <strong>a · b</strong> equals |a||b|cos(θ), substituting this reveals the standard Law of Cosines. This connection unifies planar geometry with higher-level multidimensional vector spaces.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Avoiding the Ambiguous Case</h3>
          <p>Unlike the Law of Sines, the Law of Cosines never suffers from the "ambiguous case" (SSA) when finding an angle. Why? Because the range of the principal arccosine function (cos⁻¹) is [0, π] radians or [0°, 180°].</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This perfectly matches the possible domain of interior angles in a Euclidean triangle. Therefore, a unique cosine value maps exactly to a unique angle. A positive cosine guarantees an acute angle (< 90°), a negative cosine guarantees an obtuse angle (> 90°), and a cosine of exactly zero guarantees a right angle (90°).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This robustness is why many math instructors advise using the Law of Cosines to find the largest angle first when solving SSS triangles. It mathematically eliminates any possibility of accidentally assigning an acute angle value when the true geometry requires an obtuse angle.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Applications in Navigation and Surveying</h3>
          <p>The practical applications of the Law of Cosines are vast, extending far beyond the classroom. In marine and aviation navigation, the concept of "dead reckoning" relies heavily on these principles. If a ship travels 50 nautical miles on a heading of 045°, then turns to a heading of 120° and travels 75 nautical miles, how far is it from the starting point?</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">By drawing a triangle, calculating the included angle from the headings (which would be 105°), and applying the SAS Law of Cosines, the exact linear displacement can be found instantly.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Similarly, land surveyors use a technique called triangulation. If they need to measure the distance across an impassable obstacle like a deep river canyon, they can establish a baseline on one side, measure the angles to a prominent point on the far side using a theodolite, and use trigonometric laws (both Sines and Cosines) to compute the inaccessible distance with high precision.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Solving 3D Spatial Problems</h3>
          <p>While typically taught in 2D geometry, the Law of Cosines scales up to solve three-dimensional problems. When dealing with tetrahedrons or more complex polyhedra, you frequently need to find the angles between internal diagonal lines or adjacent faces (dihedral angles).</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">By calculating the lengths of the line segments forming a triangle within the 3D space using the 3D distance formula (√(Δx² + Δy² + Δz²)), you can reduce a complex 3D angle problem into a simple 2D SSS triangle problem solvable via the Law of Cosines.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">This principle is the foundation for computer graphics engines. When rendering a 3D scene, lighting calculations depend heavily on determining the angle between a light source vector and the normal vector of a polygon face. While often optimized using dot products, the underlying mathematics is pure Law of Cosines.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>


    <div class="educational-section">
      <h2>Step-by-Step Breakdown for Solving the SSS Case</h2>
      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Step 1: The Principle of the Longest Side</h3>
          <p>When you are given three side lengths (e.g., a=5, b=7, c=10), the very first rule is to identify the longest side. In this example, side <strong>c (10)</strong> is the longest. The angle opposite the longest side will <em>always</em> be the largest angle in the triangle. This is a fundamental property of geometry.</p>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Why does this matter? Because a triangle can only have at most <em>one</em> obtuse angle (an angle strictly greater than 90°). By solving for the largest angle first using the Law of Cosines, we guarantee we will find that obtuse angle if it exists, because the inverse cosine function (cos⁻¹) correctly returns values between 90° and 180° for negative inputs.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Step 2: Calculate the Largest Angle (Angle C)</h3>
          <p>Using our identified longest side (c=10), we set up the rearranged Law of Cosines formula to solve for Angle C:</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; font-family: monospace;">
            <li>cos(C) = (a² + b² - c²) / 2ab</li>
            <li>cos(C) = (5² + 7² - 10²) / (2 * 5 * 7)</li>
            <li>cos(C) = (25 + 49 - 100) / 70</li>
            <li>cos(C) = (-26) / 70 ≈ -0.3714</li>
            <li>C = cos⁻¹(-0.3714) ≈ 111.80°</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">The negative cosine value correctly indicates an obtuse angle. If we had used the Law of Sines later to find this angle, we might have mistakenly found its acute supplement (180° - 111.80° = 68.2°).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Step 3: Finding the Second Angle (Angle B)</h3>
          <p>Now that we know one angle securely (C = 111.80°), we can find the second angle. We can use the Law of Cosines again, or we can switch to the much simpler Law of Sines.</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; font-family: monospace;">
            <li>sin(B) / b = sin(C) / c</li>
            <li>sin(B) / 7 = sin(111.80°) / 10</li>
            <li>sin(B) = 7 * (0.9285 / 10)</li>
            <li>sin(B) ≈ 0.650</li>
            <li>B = sin⁻¹(0.650) ≈ 40.54°</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Because we already found the largest angle (and it was obtuse), we know for a fact that the remaining two angles must be acute. Therefore, it is completely safe to use the Law of Sines here without worrying about the "ambiguous case".</p>
        </div>
        <div class="edu-card">
          <h3>Step 4: Finding the Final Angle (Angle A)</h3>
          <p>The final step is the easiest. The sum of all interior angles in any Euclidean planar triangle is exactly 180 degrees. Simply subtract the two known angles from 180° to find the third.</p>
          <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; font-family: monospace;">
            <li>A + B + C = 180°</li>
            <li>A + 40.54° + 111.80° = 180°</li>
            <li>A + 152.34° = 180°</li>
            <li>A = 180° - 152.34°</li>
            <li>A = 27.66°</li>
          </ul>
          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">The triangle is now completely solved. We found all three missing angles (A ≈ 27.66°, B ≈ 40.54°, C ≈ 111.80°) with high precision, starting only from the three known side lengths (a=5, b=7, c=10).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is the Law of Cosines used for? <span>+</span></div>
          <div class="faq-answer">The Law of Cosines is used to find unknown sides or angles in a triangle, especially when you know three sides (SSS) or two sides and the included angle (SAS). It's a generalization of the Pythagorean theorem for non-right triangles.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is the formula for the Law of Cosines? <span>+</span></div>
          <div class="faq-answer">The formula is c² = a² + b² - 2ab * cos(C), where a, b, and c are sides of the triangle, and C is the angle opposite side c. It can also be rearranged to solve for an angle: cos(C) = (a² + b² - c²) / (2ab).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">When should I use the Law of Cosines instead of the Law of Sines? <span>+</span></div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Use the Law of Cosines when you have SSS (Side-Side-Side) or SAS (Side-Angle-Side). Use the Law of Sines when you have a known side and its opposite known angle, like AAS, ASA, or SSA.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Can the Law of Cosines solve for right triangles? <span>+</span></div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Yes! If angle C is 90 degrees, cos(90°) = 0, so the term '- 2ab * cos(C)' becomes zero. The formula then simplifies exactly to the Pythagorean theorem: c² = a² + b².</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Can a triangle be solved if only the three angles are known? <span>+</span></div>
          <div class="faq-answer">No. Knowing only three angles (AAA) gives the shape of the triangle but not its size. There are infinitely many similar triangles with the same angles, so you need at least one side length to find exact dimensions.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="related-links">
      <h2>More Math Tools</h2>
      <div class="related-links-grid">
        <a href="/law-of-sines-calculator">Law of Sines Calculator</a>
        <a href="/right-triangle-calculator">Right Triangle Calculator</a>
        <a href="/triangle-calculator">General Triangle Calculator</a>
        <a href="/hypotenuse-calculator">Hypotenuse Calculator</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    // FAQ Toggle
    document.querySelectorAll('.faq-question').forEach(function(question) {
      question.addEventListener('click', function() {
        const item = this.parentElement;
        const isActive = item.classList.contains('active');

        // Close all
        document.querySelectorAll('.faq-item').forEach(function(fi) {
          fi.classList.remove('active');
          fi.querySelector('span').textContent = '+';
        });

        // Open clicked if it wasn't already open
        if (!isActive) {
          item.classList.add('active');
          this.querySelector('span').textContent = '-';
        }
      });
    });

    // Calculator Logic
    const D2R = Math.PI / 180;
    const R2D = 180 / Math.PI;

    const els = {
      a: document.getElementById('side-a'),
      b: document.getElementById('side-b'),
      c: document.getElementById('side-c'),
      A: document.getElementById('angle-a'),
      B: document.getElementById('angle-b'),
      C: document.getElementById('angle-c'),
      err: document.getElementById('error-message'),
      res: document.getElementById('result-section'),
      steps: document.getElementById('solution-steps'),
      svg: document.getElementById('triangle-svg')
    };

    const resEls = {
      a: document.getElementById('res-side-a'),
      b: document.getElementById('res-side-b'),
      c: document.getElementById('res-side-c'),
      A: document.getElementById('res-angle-a'),
      B: document.getElementById('res-angle-b'),
      C: document.getElementById('res-angle-c'),
      area: document.getElementById('res-area')
    };

    function showError(msg) {
      els.err.textContent = msg;
      els.err.style.display = 'block';
      els.res.style.display = 'none';
    }

    function hideError() {
      els.err.style.display = 'none';
    }

    function round(val, dec = 4) {
      return Math.round(val * Math.pow(10, dec)) / Math.pow(10, dec);
    }

    function formatStep(html) {
      return '<div class="step">' + html + '</div>';
    }

    function drawTriangle(a, b, c, A, B, C) {
      // Scale and position triangle in SVG
      // A is at bottom left (0,0 locally)
      // c is along bottom axis
      // B is at bottom right (c, 0 locally)
      // C is top point

      const width = 100; // max width of viewBox

      // Calculate coordinates
      // Point A (for angle A) at origin
      const pxA = 0;
      const pyA = 0;

      // Point B (for angle B) along x-axis
      const pxB = c;
      const pyB = 0;

      // Point C (for angle C)
      const pxC = b * Math.cos(A * D2R);
      const pyC = b * Math.sin(A * D2R);

      // Bounding box
      const minX = Math.min(pxA, pxB, pxC);
      const maxX = Math.max(pxA, pxB, pxC);
      const minY = Math.min(pyA, pyB, pyC);
      const maxY = Math.max(pyA, pyB, pyC);

      const w = maxX - minX;
      const h = maxY - minY;

      // Scale to fit 100x100 box with 10% padding
      const scale = 80 / Math.max(w, h);

      // Center the triangle
      const cx = (minX + maxX) / 2;
      const cy = (minY + maxY) / 2;

      const offsetX = 50 - (cx * scale);
      const offsetY = 50 - (cy * scale);

      // Apply scale and invert Y (SVG y goes down)
      const p1x = (pxA * scale) + offsetX;
      const p1y = 100 - ((pyA * scale) + offsetY);

      const p2x = (pxB * scale) + offsetX;
      const p2y = 100 - ((pyB * scale) + offsetY);

      const p3x = (pxC * scale) + offsetX;
      const p3y = 100 - ((pyC * scale) + offsetY);

      // Label positions (slightly pushed out from center of edges)
      const lAx = p1x - 5; const lAy = p1y + 5;
      const lBx = p2x + 5; const lBy = p2y + 5;
      const lCx = p3x; const lCy = p3y - 5;

      const lsax = (p2x + p3x)/2 + 5; const lsay = (p2y + p3y)/2;
      const lsbx = (p1x + p3x)/2 - 5; const lsby = (p1y + p3y)/2;
      const lscx = (p1x + p2x)/2; const lscy = (p1y + p2y)/2 + 8;

      els.svg.innerHTML = `
        <polygon points="${p1x},${p1y} ${p2x},${p2y} ${p3x},${p3y}" fill="rgba(var(--accent-color-rgb, 0,120,255), 0.1)" stroke="var(--accent-color)" stroke-width="2" stroke-linejoin="round" />

        <text x="${lAx}" y="${lAy}" font-size="6" fill="var(--text-primary)" text-anchor="end">A</text>
        <text x="${lBx}" y="${lBy}" font-size="6" fill="var(--text-primary)" text-anchor="start">B</text>
        <text x="${lCx}" y="${lCy}" font-size="6" fill="var(--text-primary)" text-anchor="middle">C</text>

        <text x="${lsax}" y="${lsay}" font-size="5" fill="var(--text-secondary)" text-anchor="start">a=${round(a, 1)}</text>
        <text x="${lsbx}" y="${lsby}" font-size="5" fill="var(--text-secondary)" text-anchor="end">b=${round(b, 1)}</text>
        <text x="${lscx}" y="${lscy}" font-size="5" fill="var(--text-secondary)" text-anchor="middle">c=${round(c, 1)}</text>
      `;
    }

    function solveTriangle() {
      hideError();

      let a = parseFloat(els.a.value);
      let b = parseFloat(els.b.value);
      let c = parseFloat(els.c.value);
      let A = parseFloat(els.A.value);
      let B = parseFloat(els.B.value);
      let C = parseFloat(els.C.value);

      a = isNaN(a) ? null : a;
      b = isNaN(b) ? null : b;
      c = isNaN(c) ? null : c;
      A = isNaN(A) ? null : A;
      B = isNaN(B) ? null : B;
      C = isNaN(C) ? null : C;

      let knowns = [a, b, c, A, B, C].filter(x => x !== null).length;

      if (knowns !== 3) {
        return showError("Please enter exactly three values.");
      }

      // Check for SSS
      if (a !== null && b !== null && c !== null) {
        if (a + b <= c || a + c <= b || b + c <= a) {
          return showError("Triangle Inequality Violation: The sum of any two sides must be greater than the third side.");
        }

        let stepsHtml = `<h3>Step-by-Step Solution (SSS)</h3>`;

        // Find Angle C
        C = Math.acos((a*a + b*b - c*c) / (2*a*b)) * R2D;
        stepsHtml += formatStep(`
          <strong>1. Find Angle C using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
          cos(C) = (a² + b² - c²) / 2ab<br>
          C = cos⁻¹( (${a}² + ${b}² - ${c}²) / (2 · ${a} · ${b}) )<br>
          C = cos⁻¹( (${a*a} + ${b*b} - ${c*c}) / ${2*a*b} )<br>
          C ≈ ${round(C)}°
        `);

        // Find Angle A
        A = Math.acos((b*b + c*c - a*a) / (2*b*c)) * R2D;
        stepsHtml += formatStep(`
          <strong>2. Find Angle A using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
          cos(A) = (b² + c² - a²) / 2bc<br>
          A = cos⁻¹( (${b}² + ${c}² - ${a}²) / (2 · ${b} · ${c}) )<br>
          A ≈ ${round(A)}°
        `);

        // Find Angle B
        B = 180 - A - C;
        stepsHtml += formatStep(`
          <strong>3. Find Angle B using sum of angles (180°):</strong><br>
          B = 180° - A - C<br>
          B = 180° - ${round(A)}° - ${round(C)}°<br>
          B ≈ ${round(B)}°
        `);

        displayResults(a, b, c, A, B, C, stepsHtml);
        return;
      }

      // Check for SAS
      if ((a !== null && b !== null && C !== null) ||
          (b !== null && c !== null && A !== null) ||
          (a !== null && c !== null && B !== null)) {

        let stepsHtml = `<h3>Step-by-Step Solution (SAS)</h3>`;

        if (a !== null && b !== null && C !== null) {
          // Find c
          c = Math.sqrt(a*a + b*b - 2*a*b*Math.cos(C * D2R));
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>1. Find side c using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
            c² = a² + b² - 2ab · cos(C)<br>
            c = √(${a}² + ${b}² - 2(${a})(${b})cos(${C}°))<br>
            c ≈ ${round(c)}
          `);

          // Find smaller angle first to avoid ambiguous case of sin inverse
          let angleA_cos = Math.acos((b*b + c*c - a*a) / (2*b*c)) * R2D;
          A = angleA_cos;
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>2. Find Angle A using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
            A = cos⁻¹( (b² + c² - a²) / 2bc )<br>
            A ≈ ${round(A)}°
          `);

          B = 180 - A - C;
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>3. Find Angle B (180° - A - C):</strong><br>
            B ≈ ${round(B)}°
          `);
        }
        else if (b !== null && c !== null && A !== null) {
          a = Math.sqrt(b*b + c*c - 2*b*c*Math.cos(A * D2R));
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>1. Find side a using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
            a² = b² + c² - 2bc · cos(A)<br>
            a ≈ ${round(a)}
          `);

          B = Math.acos((a*a + c*c - b*b) / (2*a*c)) * R2D;
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>2. Find Angle B using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
            B ≈ ${round(B)}°
          `);

          C = 180 - A - B;
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>3. Find Angle C (180° - A - B):</strong><br>
            C ≈ ${round(C)}°
          `);
        }
        else if (a !== null && c !== null && B !== null) {
          b = Math.sqrt(a*a + c*c - 2*a*c*Math.cos(B * D2R));
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>1. Find side b using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
            b² = a² + c² - 2ac · cos(B)<br>
            b ≈ ${round(b)}
          `);

          A = Math.acos((b*b + c*c - a*a) / (2*b*c)) * R2D;
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>2. Find Angle A using Law of Cosines:</strong><br>
            A ≈ ${round(A)}°
          `);

          C = 180 - A - B;
          stepsHtml += formatStep(`
            <strong>3. Find Angle C (180° - A - B):</strong><br>
            C ≈ ${round(C)}°
          `);
        }

        displayResults(a, b, c, A, B, C, stepsHtml);
        return;
      }

      // If we reach here, it's not SSS or SAS
      showError("This calculator specifically requires SSS (three sides) or SAS (two sides and included angle). For AAS, ASA, or SSA, please use the Law of Sines Calculator.");
    }

    function displayResults(a, b, c, A, B, C, stepsHtml) {
      // Calculate Area using Heron's formula
      const s = (a + b + c) / 2;
      const area = Math.sqrt(s * (s - a) * (s - b) * (s - c));

      resEls.a.textContent = round(a, 3);
      resEls.b.textContent = round(b, 3);
      resEls.c.textContent = round(c, 3);
      resEls.A.textContent = round(A, 3);
      resEls.B.textContent = round(B, 3);
      resEls.C.textContent = round(C, 3);
      resEls.area.textContent = round(area, 3);

      els.steps.innerHTML = stepsHtml;

      els.res.style.display = 'block';

      drawTriangle(a, b, c, A, B, C);

      els.res.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'start' });
    }


    document.getElementById('calc-btn').addEventListener('click', solveTriangle);

    document.getElementById('clear-btn').addEventListener('click', () => {
      els.a.value = '';
      els.b.value = '';
      els.c.value = '';
      els.A.value = '';
      els.B.value = '';
      els.C.value = '';
      hideError();
      els.res.style.display = 'none';
      els.svg.innerHTML = `
        <polygon points="0,100 100,100 50,13.4" fill="rgba(0,0,0,0.05)" stroke="var(--border-color)" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="5,5" />
        <text x="50" y="50" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--text-secondary)" font-size="8">Enter values to see</text>
      `;
    });

  </script>
</SiteLayout>
